When it comes to copying objects in JavaScript, what is the difference between a shallow copy and a deep copy, and when should you use each type?
For example, consider the following code:
let obj1 = {a: 1, b: 2, c: {d: 3}};
let shallowCopy = Object.assign({}, obj1);
let deepCopy = JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(obj1));
What is the difference between the shallowCopy and deepCopy objects, and in what scenarios would you choose one over the other? Please provide examples using JavaScript code.

output:
In JavaScript, when you create a copy of an object, you can either create a shallow copy or a deep copy. 
A shallow copy creates a new object with the same properties as the original object, but the values of any object properties are still references to the original object. This means that if you modify a property of the object in the shallow copy, it will also modify the original object. 
A deep copy creates a new object with all of the same properties and values as the original object, but any object properties are also copied recursively, creating new objects for each nested object. This means that modifying a property of the object in the deep copy will not affect the original object.
In the example code you provided, the `shallowCopy` variable is a shallow copy of the `obj1` object, while the `deepCopy` variable is a deep copy of the `obj1` object.
Here's an example of modifying a property of an object in a shallow copy:
```
let obj1 = {a: 1, b: 2, c: {d: 3}};
let shallowCopy = Object.assign({}, obj1);
shallowCopy.a = 4;
console.log(shallowCopy); // {a: 4, b: 2, c: {d: 3}}
console.log(obj1); // {a: 1, b: 2, c: {d: 3}}
shallowCopy.c.d = 5;
console.log(shallowCopy); // {a: 4, b: 2, c: {d: 5}}
console.log(obj1); // {a: 1, b: 2, c: {d: 5}}
```
As you can see, modifying the `a` property of the `shallowCopy` object does not affect the `obj1` object, but modifying the `d` property of the nested `c` object does affect the `obj1` object because both objects share the same reference to the nested `c` object.
Here's an example of modifying a property of an object in a deep copy:
```
let obj1 = {a: 1, b: 2, c: {d: 3}};
let deepCopy = JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(obj1));
deepCopy.a = 4;
console.log(deepCopy); // {a: 4, b: 2, c: {d: 3}}
console.log(obj1); // {a: 1, b: 2, c: {d: 3}}
deepCopy.c.d = 5;
console.log(deepCopy); // {a: 4, b: 2, c: {d: 5}}
console.log(obj1); // {a: 1, b: 2, c: {d: 3}}
```
In this case, modifying the `a` property of the `deepCopy` object does not affect the `obj1` object, and modifying the `d` property of the nested `c` object also does not affect the `obj1` object because the `deepCopy` object has its own copy of the nested `c` object.
In general, you would use a shallow copy when you only need to make a quick copy of an object and don't need to modify any nested objects. You would use a deep copy when you need to make a complete copy of an object and all of its nested objects, and you want to be able to modify the copy without affecting the original object. However, it's important to note that creating a deep copy can be more resource-intensive and time-consuming than creating a shallow copy, especially for large and complex objects.

Yes, you can send a reminder email to all team members for the upcoming meeting in C++ code using an email library like libcurl. Here's an example code snippet that demonstrates how to send an email with an attachment:
```c++
#include <curl/curl.h>
#include <string>
int main()
{
    CURL *curl;
    CURLcode res = CURLE_OK;
    struct curl_slist *recipients = NULL;
    std::string smtp_server = "smtp.gmail.com";
    std::string username = "your_username@gmail.com";
    std::string password = "your_password";
    std::string from = "your_username@gmail.com";
    std::string to = "team_member1@example.com, team_member2@example.com";
    std::string subject = "Reminder: Upcoming Meeting";
    std::string body = "Hello team,\n\nJust a friendly reminder that we have a meeting scheduled for tomorrow at 10am. Attached is the agenda and any relevant documents.\n\nBest,\nYour Name";
    std::string attachment_path = "/path/to/attachment.pdf";
    curl = curl_easy_init();
    if (curl)
    {
        curl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_USERNAME, username.c_str());
        curl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_PASSWORD, password.c_str());
        curl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_URL, smtp_server.c_str());
        curl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_USE_SSL, (long)CURLUSESSL_ALL);
        curl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_MAIL_FROM, from.c_str());
        recipients = curl_slist_append(recipients, to.c_str());
        curl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_MAIL_RCPT, recipients);
        std::string message = "From: " + from + "\r\n";
        message += "To: " + to + "\r\n";
        message += "Subject: " + subject + "\r\n";
        message += "Content-Type: multipart/mixed; boundary=frontier\r\n\r\n";
        message += "--frontier\r\n";
        message += "Content-Type: text/plain\r\n\r\n";
        message += body + "\r\n\r\n";
        message += "--frontier\r\n";
        message += "Content-Type: application/pdf\r\n";
        message += "Content-Disposition: attachment; filename=\"" + attachment_path + "\"\r\n\r\n";
        FILE *attachment_file = fopen(attachment_path.c_str(), "rb");
        if (attachment_file)
        {
            fseek(attachment_file, 0, SEEK_END);
            long attachment_size = ftell(attachment_file);
            fseek(attachment_file, 0, SEEK_SET);
            char *attachment_data = new char[attachment_size];
            fread(attachment_data, 1, attachment_size, attachment_file);
            message += std::string(attachment_data, attachment_size);
            delete[] attachment_data;
            fclose(attachment_file);
        }
        message += "\r\n--frontier--\r\n";
        curl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_READFUNCTION, NULL);
        curl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_MAIL_FROM, from.c_str());
        curl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_MAIL_RCPT, recipients);
        curl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_UPLOAD, 1L);
        curl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_READDATA, &message);
        curl_easy_setopt(curl, CURLOPT_VERBOSE, 1L);
        res = curl_easy_perform(curl);
        curl_slist_free_all(recipients);
        curl_easy_cleanup(curl);
    }
    return (int)res;
}
```
Replace `smtp_server`, `username`, `password`, `from`, `to`, `subject`, `body`, and `attachment_path` with the appropriate values for your email account and attachment file. This code sends an email with a text body and a PDF attachment to the specified recipients.

