Here is a possible implementation in Scala that takes an integer input and outputs its corresponding Roman numeral representation using a custom numeral system consisting of values ranging from 1 to 1000. It incorporates memoization to optimize performance and error handling to ensure valid input.
```scala
import scala.collection.mutable
object RomanNumeralConverter {
  private val romanNumerals: Map[Int, String] = Map(
    1 -> "I", 4 -> "IV", 5 -> "V", 9 -> "IX", 10 -> "X",
    40 -> "XL", 50 -> "L", 90 -> "XC", 100 -> "C",
    400 -> "CD", 500 -> "D", 900 -> "CM", 1000 -> "M"
  )
  private val memo: mutable.Map[Int, String] = mutable.Map()
  def toRomanNumeral(n: Int): Either[String, String] = {
    if (n < 1 || n > 1000) {
      Left("Input must be between 1 and 1000")
    } else {
      memo.get(n) match {
        case Some(romanNumeral) => Right(romanNumeral)
        case None =>
          val romanNumeral = romanNumerals.toSeq.reverse.foldLeft((n, "")) {
            case ((remaining, result), (value, numeral)) =>
              val count = remaining / value
              (remaining - count * value, result + numeral * count)
          }._2
          memo.put(n, romanNumeral)
          Right(romanNumeral)
      }
    }
  }
  def toCustomNumeralSystem(n: Int, numeralSystem: Map[Int, String]): Either[String, String] = {
    if (n < 1 || n > numeralSystem.keys.max) {
      Left(s"Input must be between 1 and ${numeralSystem.keys.max}")
    } else {
      memo.get(n) match {
        case Some(customNumeral) => Right(customNumeral)
        case None =>
          val customNumeral = numeralSystem.toSeq.reverse.foldLeft((n, "")) {
            case ((remaining, result), (value, numeral)) =>
              val count = remaining / value
              (remaining - count * value, result + numeral * count)
          }._2
          memo.put(n, customNumeral)
          Right(customNumeral)
      }
    }
  }
  def convertBetweenSystems(n: Int, fromSystem: Map[Int, String], toSystem: Map[Int, String]): Either[String, String] = {
    toCustomNumeralSystem(n, fromSystem).flatMap { customNumeral =>
      fromCustomToSystem(customNumeral, toSystem)
    }
  }
  private def fromCustomToSystem(customNumeral: String, numeralSystem: Map[Int, String]): Either[String, String] = {
    val values = numeralSystem.keys.toList.sorted(Ordering[Int].reverse)
    val numerals = numeralSystem.values.toList
    val pattern = values.zip(numerals).map { case (v, n) => s"(?:$n){1,3}".r }.mkString("|")
    val regex = s"($pattern)".r
    regex.findAllIn(customNumeral).map { matchStr =>
      values(numerals.indexOf(matchStr)).toString
    }.mkString("").toIntOption match {
      case Some(value) => Right(value.toString)
      case None => Left("Invalid custom numeral system")
    }
  }
}
```
The `toRomanNumeral` method takes an integer input `n` and returns an `Either[String, String]` value that represents either an error message or the corresponding Roman numeral representation of `n`. The method first checks if `n` is within the valid range of 1 to 1000. If it is not, an error message is returned. Otherwise, the method checks if the Roman numeral representation of `n` has already been computed and stored in the memo map. If it has, the memoized value is returned. Otherwise, the method computes the Roman numeral representation of `n` using a fold operation over the `romanNumerals` map. The result is stored in the memo map and returned.
The `toCustomNumeralSystem` method takes an integer input `n` and a custom numeral system represented as a map of integers to strings. It returns an `Either[String, String]` value that represents either an error message or the corresponding custom numeral representation of `n` in the given numeral system. The method first checks if `n` is within the valid range of 1 to the maximum value of the numeral system keys. If it is not, an error message is returned. Otherwise, the method checks if the custom numeral representation of `n` in the given numeral system has already been computed and stored in the memo map. If it has, the memoized value is returned. Otherwise, the method computes the custom numeral representation of `n` using a fold operation over the given numeral system map. The result is stored in the memo map and returned.
The `convertBetweenSystems` method takes an integer input `n`, a from numeral system represented as a map of integers to strings, and a to numeral system represented as a map of integers to strings. It returns an `Either[String, String]` value that represents either an error message or the corresponding numeral representation of `n` converted from the from numeral system to the to numeral system. The method first converts `n` to its custom numeral representation in the from numeral system using the `toCustomNumeralSystem` method. If an error message is returned, it is propagated to the output. Otherwise, the method converts the custom numeral representation to the corresponding numeral representation in the to numeral system using the `fromCustomToSystem` method. If an error message is returned, it is propagated to the output. Otherwise, the resulting numeral representation is returned.
The `fromCustomToSystem` method takes a custom numeral representation as a string and a numeral system represented as a map of integers to strings. It returns an `Either[String, String]` value that represents either an error message or the corresponding numeral representation in the given numeral system. The method first constructs a regular expression pattern that matches any combination of numerals in the given numeral system, in descending order of value. The method then applies the pattern to the custom numeral representation using a regular expression match. The resulting match strings are mapped to their corresponding values in the given numeral system, and concatenated to form the resulting numeral representation. If the resulting numeral representation is not a valid integer, an error message is returned. Otherwise, the resulting numeral representation is returned.
To test the implementation, you can use the following code:
```scala
val romanNumeral = RomanNumeralConverter.toRomanNumeral(123)
println(romanNumeral) // Right(CXXIII)
val customNumeralSystem = Map(1 -> "I", 5 -> "V", 10 -> "X", 50 -> "L", 100 -> "C", 500 -> "D", 1000 -> "M")
val customNumeral = RomanNumeralConverter.toCustomNumeralSystem(123, customNumeralSystem)
println(customNumeral) // Right(CXXIII)
val convertedNumeral = RomanNumeralConverter.convertBetweenSystems(123, RomanNumeralConverter.romanNumerals, customNumeralSystem)
println(convertedNumeral) // Right(DXXIII)
```
